-- 
Hong Kong Stocks Rise Most in Three Weeks on Europe Speculation

-- B y   J o n a t h a n   B u r g o s
-- 
2011-11-28T09:04:53Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-11-28/hong-kong-stocks-climb-on-u-s-thanksgiving-sales-europe-action-optimism.html
Hong Kong   stocks (HSI)  gained, sending the
Hang Seng Index to the biggest advance in three weeks, amid
optimism that more will be done to contain Europe’s sovereign-
debt crisis and after Thanksgiving weekend sales in the U.S.
rose to a record.  Li & Fung Ltd. (494) , the biggest supplier of clothes and toys to
retailers such as Wal-Mart Stores Inc., jumped 10 percent on
speculation shipments to the U.S. will increase.  HSBC Holdings
Plc (HSBA) , Europe’s largest lender by market value, advanced 1.8
percent ahead of a meeting by euro-area finance ministers
tomorrow in Brussels.  Cnooc Ltd. (883)  snapped a record streak of
daily losses, climbing 2.7 percent after oil rose.  “Stocks are rebounding as data suggests the  U.S. economy 
is not doing too badly,” said Cedric Ma, senior investment
strategist at Convoy Asset Management Ltd., which oversees the
equivalent of $260 million in Hong Kong. “We’ll have to see the
employment data due out this week to gauge whether the economy
is really improving. News out of Europe is also helping to bring
some calm in the market.”  The Hang Seng Index gained 2 percent, the most since Nov.
4, to 18,037.81. The gauge has fallen 9.2 percent this month as
surging bond yields in Italy and Spain stoked concern Europe’s
sovereign-debt crisis is spreading to major economies.  The  Hang Seng China Enterprises Index (HSCEI)  of mainland companies
listed in Hong Kong increased 2.3 percent to 9,609.86.  Holiday Sales  Exporters advanced after a report showed U.S. retail sales
during Thanksgiving weekend climbed 16 percent to a record as
shoppers flocked to stores earlier and spent more. A report due
on Dec. 2 is expected to show the jobless rate in the world’s
biggest economy held at 9 percent, according to a Bloomberg News
survey.  Li & Fung, which counts the U.S. as its biggest market,
climbed 10 percent to HK$15.28.  Yue Yuen Industrial Holdings
Ltd. (551) , a supplier of shoes to Nike Inc., advanced 7.5 percent to
HK$22.90.  Italian Prime Minister  Mario Monti  will propose new
austerity measures next week to help the government achieve a
balances budget by 2013, the Wall Street Journal reported,
citing a person it said was familiar with the budget. German
Finance Minister  Wolfgang Schaeuble  urged fast-track treaty
changes to tighten budget discipline to calm markets.  HSBC rose 1.8 percent to HK$57.10.  Standard Chartered Plc (STAN) ,
the U.K. lender that gets more than half of its revenue in the
Asia-Pacific region, gained 2 percent to HK$156.20.  Esprit
Holdings Ltd. (330) , the clothier that counts Europe as its biggest
market, added 1.7 percent to HK$10.06.  Cnooc Snaps Losses  Cnooc, China’s biggest offshore energy explorer, increased
2.7 percent to HK$13.86 after falling for nine days in a row.
Crude oil for January delivery advanced as much as 2.2 percent
today after rising 0.6 percent on Nov. 25.  The Hang Seng Index has declined 22 percent this year,
reducing its valuation to 9.8 times estimated earnings, compared
about 14 times at the end of 2010, according to data compiled by
Bloomberg.  China’s rail stocks gained after the Xinhua News Agency
reported on Nov. 26 that the nation’s investment in transport
infrastructure increased 12 percent to 1.14 trillion yuan ($179
billion) in the 10 months to October from a year earlier.  China Railway Group Ltd. (601390) , the country’s biggest builder of
train lines, advanced 6.3 percent to HK$2.35. CSR Corp., China’s
largest trainmaker, rose 3.3 percent to HK$4.70.  Futures on the Hang Seng Index increased 2.1 percent to
18,020. The  HSI Volatility Index  declined 9.8 percent to 32.57
for the biggest retreat in two weeks. The gauge indicates
options traders expect a swing of 9.3 percent in the benchmark
over the next 30 days.  To contact the reporter on this story:
